[2] Palestinian Authority (West Bank) and Israel, Pirbright results
Date: Tue 14 Jul 2009
Source: World Reference Laboratory for FMD (WRLFMD, Pirbright, UK):
Molecular Epidemiology (ME) report, 2009, accessed 14 Jul 2009
[abridged, edited].
<http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/2009.htm>


The ME report includes now the following data concerning 5 samples
from the Palestinian Authority Territory, West Bank, of which the
molecular sequencing has been "completed, awaiting report approval:"

Serotype: A.
Samples: PAT/1/2009; PAT/2/2009; PAT/5/2009; PAT/6/2009; PAT/8/2009.
Received: 02 Jun 2009.

It incudes also the following data pertaining to Israel, of which the
molecular sequencing is "in progress:"
Serotype: A.
Samples: ISR/1/2009; ISR/2/2009; ISR/3/2009; ISR/4/2009; ISR/5/2009;
ISR/6/2009; ISR/7/2009; ISR/8/2009; ISR/9/2009; ISR/10/2009;
ISR/11/2009; ISR/12/2009; ISR/13/2009; ISR/14/2009; ISR/15/2009;
ISR/16/2009; ISR/17/2009; ISR/18/2009.
Received: 02 Jun 2009.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the above official sources, FMDV of serotype A has been
circulating in Israel and in the territory of the Palestinian
authority (West Bank) since the beginning of 2009. Rather likely, the
virus is similar to the FMDV 'serotype A, topotype Asia, strain
Iran-05,' which has been reportedly spreading within the Middle East;
an early publication of the genotyping results of the samples from the
Palestinian territories, reportedly already completed, will be
helpful. It will also help to note the dates and locations of their
samplings.

According to the 2009 Molecular Epidemiology (ME) report of the World
Reference Laboratory for FMD (WRLFMD, Pirbright, UK), the FMDV A
Iran-05 strain, against which previous vaccine strains did not provide
satisfactory protection, has been identified during 2009 in Bahrain,
Egypt, Iraq, Iran, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, and Turkey. Jordan reported
an outbreak in December 2006.

The exceptionally high mortality in goats in the Israeli outbreak
number 7, which included high milk-yielding Saanen goats, deserves
attention.

Looking at the map of the Middle East, it seems that only one country
has not yet been, reportedly, affected by the new strain, namely
Syria. See at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/txu-oclc-192062619-middle_east_pol_2008.jpg>.
- Mod.AS]
